###How to fix the Common Vulnerabilities issue of CVE-2021-40438 in nginx web server and which owasp top 10 web 2021 category this issue belong to ?
CVE-2021-40438 is a Server Side Request Forgery (SSRF) vulnerability in the mod_proxy module of the nginx web server. This vulnerability allows an attacker to make arbitrary requests to other servers by crafting a specially-crafted URL.

To fix this vulnerability, you should upgrade to a version of nginx that includes the fix for CVE-2021-40438. You can check the nginx version you are running by using the following command:

```
nginx -V
```

If you are not running a version of nginx that includes the fix for CVE-2021-40438, you can download the latest version from the nginx website.

The CVE-2021-40438 vulnerability belongs to the OWASP Top 10 Web Application Security Risks category of Injection. Injection flaws, such as SSRF, allow attackers to inject malicious code into a vulnerable application. This malicious code can then be used to steal data, execute commands, or disrupt the application.

Here are some additional tips for preventing SSRF attacks:

* Do not allow unauthenticated users to make requests to external servers.
* Use a web application firewall (WAF) to block known SSRF attack vectors.
* Implement input validation to prevent attackers from injecting malicious code into requests.
* Keep your web server software up to date with the latest security patches.

By following these tips, you can help to protect your web applications from SSRF attacks.
